			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ok, I did some math, because I'm puzzled at this. What I turned up was somewhat interesting.
<br />

<br />
Wizards chaincasting Strike of Solusek (2740 dmg) and Concussion (less aggro), disreguarding mana consumption and assuming an overall +25% per strike due to crit rate (3425 dmg), without casting time haste.
<br />

<br />
Without Elem Pants (14.5 cast time) - 236 DPS
<br />
With Elem Pants (10.25 cast time) - 335 DPS
<br />

<br />
Same as above, with +15% spell haste.
<br />

<br />
Without Elem Pants (13 cast time) - 263 DPS
<br />
With Elem Pants (9.05 cast time) - 378 DPS
<br />

<br />
I'm finding that Elemental Pants give wizards around a 42% boost to their damage rate when using Strike of Solusek. It's good, I'll admit that, but wonder if people are assuming this 100% increase in damage or if there is actual proof of a higher damage improvement or not.
<br />

<br />
Anyways, back on topic as to why this info is important, magician pure spell damage ratios.
<br />

<br />
Magician chain casting FBoT (most gods are big enough that this is ok to do) (2000 dmg) with a near 6 second pause to control aggro with an overall +14% damage due to crit rate, without spell haste.
<br />

<br />
FBoT (15 cast/recovery time) - 152 DPS
<br />

<br />
Now, I'm sure you go OMG, how pathetic in comparison, but let's throw in the pet damage. Against most mobs, even high level, Ward of Xegony pulls around 60-70 DPS in pure melee. Servant can pull off 90 DPS in it's proper backstab position. So, we're at...
<br />

<br />
FBoT chain cast/pause + Ward (60-70 DPS) = 212-222 DPS
<br />
FBoT chain cast/pause + Servant (90 DPS) = 242 DPS
<br />

<br />
220 DPS (ave num in that range) compared to non-elemental pant'd wizard of 236 DPS. Not so far off, and magicians have in reserve Frenzy, Servant, and Host. Focus effects between the classes can be considered even in most cases.
<br />

<br />
I guess the problem is that wizards with elemental pants can seriously improve their damage while magicians cannot, and nothing in the planes now can really do anything to boost that figure (Symb of Ancient Summoning? <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="Razz" border="0" />)
<br />

<br />
Of course, these numbers are theoretical, and have some assumptions and pieces left out. Any particular proof that wizards are kicking our ass in damage, beyond times we cannot use our pet?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
