				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm not suggesting we get root/snare/TL etc what I'm saying is these are super spells that mages do not have, and that are not taken into concideration when comparing the two classes.  If wizards are THE damage class then what is the mage. We have the druids that can nuke as well as us and then turn around and be in a heal rotation with their great heals, and then fill in as a evacer/porter etc.
<br />

<br />
We mages do not have anything else but damage.  Our DS is about 17 DPS on avarage, our pets for arugement sake is 50 DPS on raid mobs.  We need to do a slow nuke that is about 150 DPS or we die.  Now this is all in the best situations add in we can't use a pet, or the mob is fire/magic resistent and our DPS drops to crap.
<br />

<br />
To say we have mod rod or any of our other utility spells is saying we need just one mage on a raid but those 10 wizards are a must.
<br />

<br />
Everything about a mage is damage in a fight.  Name a spell we cast in the middle of a fight that is not a damage spell.  Before the fight we cast mass mod rod and DS and maybe coh (2 btw being level mid 50 spells). That is it, so to say the wizards are THE damage class is saying you need only one level 56 mage on a hugh raid to handle any CoH/ mass mod rod and maybe not a 45 DS but he has a 33 DS, and then have all your  caster damage from wizards.
<br />

<br />
My argument is wizard and mages should be somewhat interchangeable
<br />
as top damage dealers and we are not. To narrow the DPS field between the two classes and increase the mage damage usefullness in more situations would fix this and the guild with 2 wizards and 10 mages would be able to do about the same as a guild with 2 mages and 10 wizards.
<br />

<br />
There is a stranglehold on guilds because there is not enough wizards to go around for them to climb the tier ladder effectively and that is not right when you have another caster damage class (mages) that should be able to fill those shoes too.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
