				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>xtro wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'm not suggesting we get root/snare/TL etc what I'm saying is these are super spells that mages do not have, and that are not taken into concideration when comparing the two classes.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Balanz wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Right, but it is very difficulty to compare those to pets, which is why I suggest that as a first guess, assume they are roughly equal.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The bottom line to me is that our offensive output isn't nearly high enough to justify our complete lack of natural (aka Spell based) defensive capabilities. Sure pets can be used for this, but it is more random, and less reliable than adding player based abilities. Wizards have a definate edge, even at first glance, because player based spells are more predictable and controlled than pet based abilities. 
<br />

<br />
One of the things that does disappoint me when I compare the two classes are the number of things that work against magician spell damage.
<br />

<br />
Longer cast time, worse dmg/mana ratio, higher aggro / no aggro mitigation, more limited spell resist selection (though we do have debuffs, those are somewhat balanced by Wizard lures). 
<br />

<br />
Perhaps removing one or two of the limiting effects on our spells, without giving us extra abilities may be a way to go.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=381929&resize=true" target="_blank" class="postlink">Naladini Dreamfyre</a>
<br />
Arch Mage of 61 Seasons - <a href="http://www.stormhammer.org/forums" target="_blank" class="postlink">Stormhammer*</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
