				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">...just like comparing a paladin to a warrior.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">And this is exactly what class balance is all about.  How can one possibly know whether tank classes are balanced except by comparing them?  How can one know whether damage dealer casters are balanced except by comparing them?
<br />

<br />
If one cannot compare classes, what then is the meaning of class balance?
<br />

<br />
Indeed, the reason that some on this board have concluded that there is a problem is exactly because of such a comparison.  Mages and wizards are both damage dealing classes, yet wizards are eagerly recruited by raiding guilds while mages are not.  A mage should be a close substitute for a wizard on a raid, otherwise we are just conjure-bots.
<br />

<br />
Contrarywise, if mages were able to consistantly outnuke wizards, it would absurd to argue that one should not compare wizards with mages.
<br />

<br />
One can and does compare apples and oranges, and by several means: cost, weight, vitamin content, availability.  Likewise, one compares wizards and mages, warriors and paladins, clerics and shaman, enchanters and bards, and so on.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Razamatazz Pizzazz</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
